<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Body length: male 14.5-15 mm, female 15.5-16 mm. This is a species with a black body and blackish wings with a large whitish apical wing mark. From similarly coloured species (
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. bispina" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="bispina">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. bispina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. normalis" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="normalis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. normalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. pompiloides" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="pompiloides">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. pompiloides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) this species differs by the entirely microtrichose alula.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
The two specimens from Mexico (including the type of 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. niger" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="niger">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. niger</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) are males, whereas the two specimens from Bolivia (i.e., the type of 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. manni" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="manni">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. manni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and Peru are both females. Apart from usual sexual dimorphism, no morphological differences could be found. This supports the synonymization of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Microdon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Microdon manni" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="manni">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Microdon manni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Shannon with 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. niger" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="niger">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">M. niger</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Williston by 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.5962/bhl.title.49898" author="Thompson, FC" journalOrPublisher="A catalogue of the Diptera of the Americas south of the United States" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="1 - 195" refId="B29" refString="Thompson, FC, Vockeroth, JR, Sedman, YS, 1976. Family Syrphidae. A catalogue of the Diptera of the Americas south of the United States 46: 1 - 195" title="Family Syrphidae." url="https://doi.org/10.5962/bhl.title.49898" volume="46" year="1976">Thompson et al. (1976)</bibRefCitation>
. However, the type localities of these taxa (Bolivia and Mexico, respectively) are far apart, and the types are of opposite sexes. Support for this synonymy would be stronger if males and females of both areas could be compared with each other.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Known from southern Mexico and Amazonian parts of Bolivia and Peru.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
